or do that will impact their members teaching (or not teaching as the case may be).  The department of education sets the curriculum and it is done with minimal consultation with parents - some how we are deemed competent to run corporations but not competent to determine what our children should be learning.    Many of these issues (minus the union) are also present at private schools.  However the author's reasoning that we are bad parents if we were to choose to educate our children privately sounds more like sour grapes.  If she cannot afford to send her children there, perhaps they can apply for scholarship - every school has them - the alumni fund them.  But the PC verging into socialist rhetoric of the huddle masses being denied is rubbish.   I voted for option 3.  We homeschool. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1105" language="en" documentId="2481" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="LiliinTo" date="Aug 29, 2013 9:36PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="11" thumbsDown="0" origId="2481" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1105"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>